# Plan — CivicQ Landing Page Demo

## 1. Demo Concept

Build the actual deliverable: a full, production-quality 10-section CivicQ
home page plus a `/methodology` page, in a bespoke civic-tech dark design
system. This is not a mockup of the idea, it is the literal page the client
asked for, built to spec, with all three required data visualizations working
and a real email-capture-to-CSV backend. The demo doubles as the portfolio
answer to "can you build this" and as the proof for all four to-apply asks.

## 2. Prototype vs Full Decision

**Decision: FULL build.** None of the three fallback triggers apply:

1. Hero feature (10-section page + methodology page) needs no backend
   integration that can't be stubbed; it's pure front-end build-to-spec.
2. Estimated footprint fits the caps (see Scope Fences below): ~12 files,
   well inside the file cap, no exotic tooling.
3. The concept is explicitly a working, clickable, functional page, not a
   visual-only idea. A static mockup would actively undersell the "build to
   spec" pitch.

The one piece of real backend work (email capture + CSV export) is small,
well-scoped, and directly proves a named requirement, so it stays in scope as
Supporting Feature 2 rather than being downgraded to a fallback.

Target feature richness is 10/10: build all 10 sections, the methodology
page, all 3 real coded data visualizations, and a working backend-backed
email capture with CSV export, polished to look like a real institutional
nonprofit product, not a wireframe.

## 3. Design Direction (bespoke, civic-tech, NOT michaelwegter.com's theme)

The client explicitly forbids redesigning their existing dark-mode system, so
since we don't have their literal tokens, the demo uses a faithful,
disciplined "institutional civic tech" stand-in palette and type system —
restrained, neutral, nonpartisan, data-forward. No red/blue partisan coding
anywhere.

**Palette**
- Background base: `#0B0E11` (near-black, slightly cool, not pure black)
- Surface / card: `#13171C`
- Surface elevated / hover: `#1A1F26`
- Border / hairline: `#262C34`
- Primary text: `#E7EAEE`
- Secondary / muted text: `#9AA4B1`
- Accent (single, institutional, NOT red/blue partisan): `#3DBFA8` (a calm
  teal, "record" / verified-data color), used sparingly for CTAs, active nav
  state, and chart highlights
- Secondary accent / warm neutral (for "in development" status, NOT alarmist
  red): `#C9A227` (muted gold), used only for IN DEVELOPMENT status pills
- LIVE status pill: teal `#3DBFA8` on `#10221D` background
- IN DEVELOPMENT status pill: gold `#C9A227` on `#221C0E` background
- Chart palette (6-dimension scoring chart, color-blind-safe, sequential):
  teal-to-gray ramp (`#3DBFA8`, `#5FB8C9`, `#7FA8C9`, `#8C97AC`, `#9AA4B1`,
  `#6E7884`) — avoids hue-based partisan reading, relies on a single
  perceptually ordered ramp plus labels/patterns for accessibility.
- Funds breakdown chart: same teal/gray family, each segment additionally
  labeled with category + dollar amount (not color-dependent).

**Typography**
- Headlines: "Newsreader" (Google Fonts) — a serif with institutional,
  editorial, "official record" gravity, used at display sizes only.
- Body / UI: "Inter" (Google Fonts) — neutral, highly legible, accessible at
  small sizes, used for body copy, nav, forms, buttons.
- Numerals / data labels: Inter with tabular-nums for the data visualizations
  so figures align cleanly.

**Mood / Tone**
- Calm authority. Generous whitespace, hairline borders instead of heavy
  shadows, no gradients-as-decoration, no large animated hero graphics beyond
  the requested video thumbnail. Motion is restrained (subtle fades/slides on
  scroll-into-view, all wrapped in `prefers-reduced-motion` guards) per the
  "lean build, no unnecessary animation" requirement.
- Status pills, two-column disclosures, and three-column cards all use the
  same border/radius/spacing system so the page reads as one disciplined
  design system, not assembled sections.

**Layout**
- Sticky top nav, anchor-linked to all 10 sections, with scroll-spy active
  state in the accent teal.
- Max content width ~1200px, fluid down to 390px with a single-column
  collapse for grids (2x2 feature grid -> 1 column; two-column disclosure ->
  stacked; three-column partners -> stacked).
- Section rhythm: consistent vertical padding scale so the page feels
  machine-consistent (institutional), reinforcing "build to spec, not
  redesigned."

## 4. Hero Feature

**The 10-section home page + /methodology page, built to spec, in order:**

1. Hero — headline + sub-copy (placeholder CivicQ voice copy), video
   thumbnail (poster image + play affordance, no real video needed),
   primary CTA ("See How Scoring Works" -> anchors to section 4) + secondary
   CTA ("Explore the Organization Hub" -> anchors to section 6).
2. Problem statement — single-column editorial text block (Newsreader
   headline + Inter body), framing civic information opacity.
3. Feature card grid — 2x2 grid, 4 cards, each with a LIVE or IN DEVELOPMENT
   status pill, icon, title, one-line description.
4. Scoring methodology visualization — the six-dimension weighted chart
   (Data Viz #1, see below), with a short explanatory caption and a link to
   `/methodology`.
5. Honest status disclosure — two-column layout, "Live Today" vs. "In
   Development," each a bulleted list, visually distinguished by the pill
   colors established in section 3.
6. Organization Hub section — the wireframe mockup (Data Viz #3, see below)
   alongside copy explaining org/researcher access, plus the email capture
   form (Supporting Feature 2).
7. Fundraising module — the $75K funds breakdown graphic (Data Viz #2, see
   below), GoFundMe CTA button (placeholder href, clearly labeled), framed as
   launch-critical.
8. Partners / Press / Orgs — three-column card section, placeholder logos/
   names with link-outs (can be `#` placeholders, clearly marked as
   illustrative).
9. Feedback banner + footer — a slim sticky-on-scroll feedback callout
   ("See something wrong? Tell us.") plus a real footer: nav links, copyright,
   nonpartisan disclaimer line (matches the posting's own disclaimer).
10. Sticky nav — implemented as the page-wide nav bar referenced above;
    placeholder search icon + auth button (visually present, non-functional,
    clearly within scope as "integrates with existing search/auth UI" since
    real auth lives outside this demo).

`/methodology` page: same design system, dedicated route, holds the fuller
explanation of the six-dimension scoring methodology (expanded prose + the
same or a detail variant of Data Viz #1), reachable from the nav and from the
hero/section-4 link.

## 5. Supporting Features

**Supporting Feature 1 — Three coded data visualizations (no library
placeholders, no designer assets):**
1. Six-dimension weighted scoring chart: a custom SVG-coded weighted bar
   chart (each of the 6 dimensions as a horizontal bar, length = weight
   percentage, labeled with dimension name + weight, animated draw-in on
   scroll, reduced-motion-safe, full ARIA labeling and a visually-hidden data
   table fallback for screen readers).
2. $75K funds breakdown graphic: custom SVG-coded stacked/segmented bar
   (not a pie, for better label legibility and accessibility) showing
   category allocations that sum exactly to $75,000, each segment labeled
   with category name + dollar figure + percentage directly on/near the
   segment (not legend-only, for color-blind safety).
3. Organization Hub wireframe mockup: a coded SVG/HTML "product shot" — a
   stylized browser-chrome frame containing a mock dashboard UI (search bar,
   a few data rows, a chart thumbnail) styled in the same dark system, so it
   reads as an intentional, near-production screenshot rather than a gray
   box wireframe.

**Supporting Feature 2 — Working email capture + CSV export (mw-backend):**
- New `civicq_blueprint.py` in mw-backend, modeled directly on
  `spotify_blueprint.py`'s structure, registered in `server.py`.
- `POST /civicq/subscribe` — validates email, stores `{email, created_at}` in
  SQLite (new small table), returns JSON success/duplicate/invalid.
- `GET /civicq/csv-export` — returns all captured emails as a CSV download
  (proves the "Mailchimp/ConvertKit + CSV backup" requirement with real
  persistence, not a claim).
- Frontend form: client-side email validation, fetch-based submit (no page
  reload), inline success/error state, associated `<label>`, ARIA live
  region for the result message.

**Minor support (woven through, not separate build items):**
- LIVE / IN DEVELOPMENT status pill component reused in sections 3 and 5.
- Scroll-spy sticky nav with active-section highlighting.
- Lightweight analytics hook: a small `track(eventName)` stub wired to a
  Plausible-style `<script>` tag placeholder + console-logged custom events
  on key interactions (CTA clicks, form submit), documented as
  "drop in real Plausible/Fathom site-id at launch."
- Accessibility pass: semantic landmarks (`nav`, `main`, `section`,
  `footer`), skip-to-content link, visible focus rings, 4.5:1 / 3:1 contrast
  checked against the palette above, alt text on all images/icons, ARIA
  labels on status pills and icon-only buttons, `prefers-reduced-motion`
  guards on all scroll animations.
- Responsive verification at 390px and 1440px (and the fluid range between).

## 6. Scope Fences (explicit exclusions, recorded so nothing creeps)

- No real GoFundMe integration, no real Mailchimp/ConvertKit account, no real
  Plausible/Fathom site id, no real search/auth backend, no real video file.
  All are clearly-labeled, functional-looking placeholders/stand-ins, per
  CLAUDE.md's "default demo form" guidance and the run's token budget.
- No redesign of CivicQ's real tokens (we don't have them); the stand-in
  system above is explicitly documented in the proposal as a faithful
  placeholder to be swapped for the client's real tokens on day one.
- No CMS, no multi-page site beyond home + `/methodology`.
- No partisan color coding anywhere, ever, including in chart palettes.

## 7. Build Approach / File Footprint (within the ~12-file cap)

Self-contained static-feel build using a small Vite + React app (warrants a
bundler given client/server fetch wiring + multiple routes/components),
output built to `../michaelwegter.com/public/demos/civicq/` with
`base: '/demos/civicq/'`.

Planned files (~11, within cap):
1. `index.html`
2. `src/main.jsx`
3. `src/App.jsx` (routes: `/` and `/methodology`)
4. `src/pages/Home.jsx` (composes the 10 sections)
5. `src/pages/Methodology.jsx`
6. `src/components/StickyNav.jsx`
7. `src/components/StatusPill.jsx`
8. `src/components/charts/ScoringChart.jsx` (Data Viz #1)
9. `src/components/charts/FundsBreakdown.jsx` (Data Viz #2)
10. `src/components/charts/OrgHubMockup.jsx` (Data Viz #3)
11. `src/components/EmailCaptureForm.jsx` + `src/styles.css` (treat as one
    combined unit if an extra file is needed; section content for items 1-3,
    5, 8, 9 can live as data/markup inline in `Home.jsx` rather than separate
    files to stay under the cap)

Backend: 1 additional file in mw-backend (`civicq_blueprint.py`) plus a
one-line registration edit in `server.py` — outside the demo's own file cap
since it's a separate repo.

## 8. Milestone / Timeline Plan (for the cover letter)

Maps directly to the client's 2-4 week window and the to-apply ask for a
concrete estimate:

- **Week 1 (Milestone 1, ~40% of fixed price):** Design-system study against
  real CivicQ staging tokens, structure all 10 sections + sticky nav to spec,
  responsive scaffold at 390px/1440px.
- **Week 2 (Milestone 2, ~40% of fixed price):** Build all three coded data
  visualizations (scoring chart, funds breakdown, Org Hub mockup), wire email
  capture form to backend with CSV export, integrate analytics hooks.
- **Week 3-4 (Milestone 3, ~20% of fixed price):** Polish, full accessibility
  audit (WCAG 2.1 AA, keyboard nav, contrast, reduced-motion), Lighthouse
  85+ tuning, cross-device QA, `/methodology` page finalization, handoff.
- Flag explicitly in the cover letter: the GoFundMe hard-launch dependency is
  a known external blocker, the funds module and CTA will be built launch-
  ready on schedule regardless of campaign-side timing.

